2023- A year of continued enlightenment and healing.

 A focus of fostering the confidence to strengthen the power and pride of cultural identity. To stand tall in the face of adversity and push through the barriers that separate us rather than unite our magnificent diversity! 

 2022 ended with a door opening... I received my Certificate of Indian Status! 🧡🦅🙌🏽 A recognition and confirmation of my mother and father's traditional and ancestral roots... and mine too! 
After MANY years of navigating through limited information, the creator has guided me on this powerful and breathtaking journey of clarity.
 I have been able to connect with my birth family and learn about our challenging history. I have also made it a point to be of service to indigenous healing and empowerment locally. This past year, I have been working with Federal corrections to hold space and ceremony with Elders and the Indigenous Trans identifying Two-Spirit population as well speaking and grounding discussions for federal training on Diversity and Inclusion.

I realize the importance of my visibility as an Indigenous Two-Spirit transgender Sober human being and Sixties Scoop Surviver and I can finally say that I truly believe the best is yet to come.

To have the ability to ease suffering in another spirit is the greatest gift of all. 🙏🏽🧡🦅

Blessings to all for a year filled with hope, health, love and joy 
 Grateful for another day walking on this earth. 

All my Relations 

Jaylene

social_posts.post_text: Try me... I'm feeling good. 🤗🦅✊🏽🧡🏳️‍⚧️🫶🏽

My live performance from Legends Cabaret tonight. 🎶
 When I was a young child I loved to sing.
I reached a point in my life where the confusion of my identity led me to lose confidence in almost everything. Experiencing an anxiety that limited me from healthy communication and in social situations I would get lost in these insecurities. 
 Drag had helped me find confidence and lipsync became an art I could express myself through. For a long time I wanted to sing again with my drag identity, but again the confidence issue mixed with a gender dysphoria of my voice really limited me. I have sang a few times, but I had not experienced the confidence. 
 With that being said, I have been doing a lot of healing over the years and part of that focus is to lean into the gift of being Two Spirit. Honouring both my masculine and feminine qualities including my singing voice.

I mentioned in a previous post that a fellow performer mentioned that it would be a good idea for me to work on some live tracks for my cabaret brand. 

So hear I go! I'm building that confidence! Moving forward, every Legend show, I will have one live singing performance! 

My trans experience includes facing my fears head on! Time to rise up! 
I have to admit that the surge of courage feels real good 🙏🏽🧡🦅🎶🎤🫶🏽🏳️‍⚧️

"This is the first International Women’s Day March in Vancouver! 

Firstly, the organizers of this event acknowledge that our march takes place on the unceded traditional territories of the xʷməθkʷəy̓əm (Musqueam), Sḵwx̱wú7mesh (Squamish), and səlilwətaɬ (Tsleil-Waututh) Nations.

We have always wanted to raise awareness about issues of gender inequity and create spaces where our community feels seen and heard. Organizing this march is our way of creating a space where ALL woman-identifying people, gender-diverse folks - and allies - can join in celebrating women and having their voices heard about the social injustices that affect women all over the world. 

The event will take place on March 5t at šxʷƛ̓ənəq Xwtl'e7énḵ Square (Vancouver Art Gallery North Plaza). From 12 to 2 PM, we will be listening to a series of speakers delivering their take on various gender- and women-related topics. Following the speeches, the rally will begin at 2 PM at West Georgia St. It will move along Howe Street to Helmcken St. There, we will walk north for a block before making a turn toward Hornby Street, which will lead us back to the art gallery, where the march will end.

Hope to see you all! 💜

‼️Please note that we intend this event to be an inclusive and safe space for all. As such, any discriminatory behaviour and hate speech will not be tolerated. ‼️"

“She sat at the back and they said she was shy,
She led from the front and they hated her pride,
They asked her advice and then questioned her guidance,
They branded her loud, then were shocked by her silence,
When she shared no ambition they said it was sad,
So she told them her dreams and they said she was mad,
They told her they'd listen, then covered their ears,
And gave her a hug while they laughed at her fears,
And she listened to all of it thinking she should,
Be the girl they told her to be best as she could,
But one day she asked what was best for herself,
Instead of trying to please everyone else,
So she walked to the forest and stood with the trees,
She heard the wind whisper and dance with the leaves,
She spoke to the willow, the elm and the pine,
And she told them what she'd been told time after time,
She told them she felt she was never enough,
She was either too little or far far too much,
Too loud or too quiet, too fierce or too weak,
Too wise or too foolish, too bold or too meek,
Then she found a small clearing surrounded by firs,
And she stopped...and she heard what the trees said to her,
And she sat there for hours not wanting to leave,

This weekend is a time to celebrate the 'Mother'. In my lifetime I have come to learn that this role can include many different people. My experience includes- the mother who gave birth to me, the mother who raised me and also my LGBTQ2S+ chosen mothers Justine Tyme @justine.tyme.18  Empress 1 Charity  Queen Mother 1 of the Americas @nicolemurrayramirez 

When I left home after high school, I felt like I had to start over. I entered into adulthood not quite knowing where to go and who I was to become. Along my journey I became a part of a family within the LGBTQ2S+ community. It was quite common for the people I knew to be estranged from their families. I find it interesting and powerful that these people would shift in to the different family roles. Sisters,brothers,siblings,mothers, and your fathers!
 When I was young in the community, I gravitated towards the Drag Community (Surprise) I remember being afraid of them but at the same time I felt such a close connection. These were the people I saw raising money for the community, entertaining crowds and making people laugh. They were also the ones who would step in if someone was giving you a hard time!  There was a humour that would overshadow life confusions and when someone was truly in need, their couch became the place of refuge.

 I also have the gift of being considered a Drag "Mom". I take great pride in fostering loving friendships with them, to celebrate their own journeys and self discoveries. It has also been an opportunity to honour those who came before me and helped guide me to find myself and realize what is most important in life ... Hold your head held high and courageously share your beautiful authenticity with the world. Be gracious and kind, get involved with community and be good to yourself and others. 

  So, whether  you are a mother to a child, to a pet or to a drag artist ! Thank you for sharing your compassion, strength and inspiration with your loved ones. 🙏🏽🪶🧡🏳️‍⚧️🏳️‍🌈👑🫶🏽🥰😭

Fathers Day:

You may be the blood that flows through our veins or you may have stepped in to the role through a divine intervention. However so, you are the vision of strength, safety and inspiration to your children. We watch you with eyes of wonderment and absorb your human spirit. As we grow we never stop longing for your approval. We hit great achievement and push through adversity with your soul running through us. The choices we make in our lives are a result of our connection to you. We remember your vulnerability but speak of your strength. With maturity we are able to acknowledge the reality of our relationship. If there has been a wounded relationship between us, we put in perspective what the underlying reasons are and do our best to walk through a healing process. If reconciliation is not possible, we realize that we can choose our father figure. 
 We move forward with the realization that the person who at one point in our lives seemed larger than life, was once a child themselves. They were searching for understanding and doing the best with the skills they had. 
 This is the circle of life and on this day we thank these men/humans for being an example of the beautiful yet complex journey that being a father represents. 
 
 Happy Fathers day. 🙏🏽🧡🦅

I created this video in 2020 when we were all in lock down.  I will post it one more time in honour. 🙏🏽❤️The feelings at the time were vulnerable and filled with uncertainty.  Art has always been my go to during challenging times, and the drag community needed to shift and present our art online. I wanted to capture one of my favorite songs in video, so I created a little set and filmed this. 🎥💡❤️

 I remember the first time I saw this video. It was a simple video, but was chock-full of emotion and beauty. I remember watching it with some friends and we were all moved to tears from it. Sinead O'Connor was a brilliant songstress and story teller. 🙌🏽🙏🏽

 With the recent passing of Sinead O'Connor and many others recently, I find myself very aware that people in the world are hurting. 
  I urge anyone reading this to reach out to your loved ones and to check in and encourage 'real' conversations. We truly need each other and sometimes people feel like they don't wanna bother others with their challenges. Many lives are crossing to the spirit world too soon.

Sending all my love. I want to make it clear that I am a person that you can reach out to you. I'm not a therapist, but I can guide you to help and I truly care. 🙏🏽🧡🪶

WHEN A COUNTRY ADOPTS 2SLGBTIQ+ INCLUSIVE LEGISLATION, THE RESPECTIVE FLAG SHALL BE REPLACED WITH A RAINBOW FLAG. 🏳️‍🌈

1st look: 

My first look was to honour the Empress of Canada ted northe and the legacy of her impact towards the decriminalization of homosexuality in Canada 1969.  It was on the steps of this building where ted protested out front holding a sign that stated "I am a human being!" As Empress 35 @dmsvancouver and Heir Apparent -1st in line of succession to Queen Mother I of the Americas Nicole Murray Ramirez , I am part of an organization @internationalcourtsystem65 where our mandate is the fight for our human rights. An international  2SLGBTIQ+ organization created by Absolute Empress 1 Josè Sarria in 1965 with chapters in over 60 cities in United States, Mexico and Canada. 👑🇺🇸🇨🇦🇲🇽🏳️‍🌈🏳️‍⚧️✊🏽

2nd look:
 
Located on the steps of the Art Gallery, where the Every Child Matters 🧡 memorium was for over two years, I knew I wanted to share visibility of my identity as a Indigenous Two- Spirit Transgender human being. A sixties scoop adoptee myself, my work in this world is to contribute to the healing of our people. 🙏🏽🧡🦅 This is a very special image for me. This is a milestone for me. 
I am 25 Years Sober from Alcohol and Drugs! 🥳😭🦅🧡
 
My name is Jaylene and I am an alcoholic and an addict. One of the most powerful statements I have ever made. 
 For it was the acceptance of these words that allowed me to create a life beyond my imagination. A healing journey of self discovery that continues to strengthen and reveal itself to me.
As a Sixties Scoop adoptee (separated from my Indigenous culture and raised by settlers), I continue on a healing journey of clarity and reclamation.  The majority of my birth family has lost their lives due to the effects of addiction and colonization. Sadly, many crossed to the spirit world through horrific and traumatic experiences. 
 Stories have been shared with me of the intergenerational trauma my family had experienced. While I have been devastated to hear of this pain, I am also grateful have answers that connect me closer to my ancestors, our history and also the opportunity to meet and build relationships with family members that walk the earth today. 🪶🙏🏽🧡

  On this milestone anniversary, I reflect on how many loved ones I have known that have lost their battle to the disease of addiction.
 During my own active using, I experienced drug overdoses along with soul crushing discrimination and transphobia with life threatening abuse. I lived within the street community of the Downtown Eastside and was reduced to a shell of a human being through my drug use.  I could have easily become another missing Indigenous statistic, but instead I am here, to share my message of recovery.  A message that states loudly, we can and do recover, together! One day at a time . Our stories are sacred and all of our voices matter.

I am an Indigenous, Two-Spirit, Sober, Transgender Warrior and I truly feel like I'm just getting started.

Please reach out if you think you have a problem with alcohol and drugs. You are NOT alone and there is help. 

We are strong, We are brave and we do recover!

World Aids Day 2023 

An International day of respect and honour. An acknowledgment of the lives affected by HIV and AIDS .  Steeped in the memories of the beautiful lives taken too soon. The awe inspiring strides in education and medical advancements that have saved countless lives and removed the death sentence once attached to a HIV positive diagnosis. 

As a teenager in the 80’s , I remember the fear, horrendous discrimination and stigmas attached to HIV/AIDS.  I came out into a community that had unfortunately become used to losing vibrant lives to this disease. While there was much sadness, I also remember the courage and the support from the LGBTQ2S+ community. Fundraisers from the Calgary Imperial Court, hair salons drives, drag shows, fashion shows , auctions... All initiatives to provide the support and resources to those effected by HIV/AIDS  that continue to this day!  I am grateful that I witnessed this- my connection to the 2SLGBTQQIA+ community was fostered in the legacy of this history.  Extended family is impactful, comforting, affirming and powerful! 

Today and every day we honour our family. ❤️ Our beloved mothers, fathers, siblings  and our friends. 
Every life matters and we must make it clear that we will continue to share the stories and champion the strength of each and every person... each and every inspiring soul. 

Together for each other 🙏🏼❤️

Compassion, education , liberation and love ❤️
